### 1. One-Line Summary
* MX-P is the harder, faster, more direct “power ESN” rubber with a strong top end and crisp contact, while Rakza 7 Soft is the softer, safer, more forgiving allround-offensive rubber with easier access to spin and control.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:**
        * MX-P: Needs a bit more input; can feel springy but not “free speed” unless you engage the sponge.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Easier pace from compact strokes; softer sponge helps the ball sink and rebound without forcing.
    * **Top End:**
        * MX-P: Higher ceiling—more direct acceleration and finishing power when you swing hard.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Good top speed, but compresses earlier; less “kill gear” on full power.
    * **Linearity:**
        * MX-P: More catapult jump when engaged; very strong when you hit through, but demands timing.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: More linear and predictable across gears; less sudden kick.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:**
        * MX-P: Heavy spin possible, but opening requires good brush + acceleration; less forgiving if you’re late.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Easiest opener—soft sponge and dwell make lifting backspin simpler and safer.
    * **Max Spin:**
        * MX-P: Higher peak spin with quality contact and speed; rewards advanced brushing under power.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: High spin, but peak is slightly lower; excels at “usable spin” rather than absolute maximum.
    * **Topsheet Grip:**
        * MX-P: Very grippy, more bite on fast brushing; excels in high-tension, high-RPM contact.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Grippy and stable; feels more “holding” and forgiving on imperfect contact.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:**
        * MX-P: Medium throw with a more forward, penetrating trajectory when driven.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Medium-high arc; naturally clears the net more easily.
    * **Safety:**
        * MX-P: Lower margin if you over-drive or mistime; rewards precision.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Higher safety window, especially on opening and mid-distance topspin.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:**
        * MX-P: Crisp, lively, “clean” impact; clearer feedback on contact quality.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Softer, more muted and cushioned; easier on the hand, less sharp feedback.
    * **Dwell:**
        * MX-P: Moderate dwell; best when you compress/engage the sponge decisively.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Longer dwell; helps spin creation and control on slower strokes.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:**
        * MX-P: More reactive to incoming spin due to tension/catapult; needs a disciplined touch.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Less reactive; easier to keep pushes/receives low and controlled.
    * **Touch Play:**
        * MX-P: Very capable, but catapult can pop the ball up if your hand is passive.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Strong in touch—dropshots, short push, and flick control feel more natural.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:**
        * MX-P: Stable if your angle is correct; faster rebound can punish small mistakes.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: More absorbing; easier to “hold” the block and control placement.
    * **Active Counter:**
        * MX-P: Excellent for punch/counter-drive—direct speed and bite shine.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Very good for controlled counter-topspin; slightly less explosive through the ball.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose MX-P if:**
    * You prioritize a higher top-end gear for finishing and mid/far-distance power.
    * Your technique reliably engages the sponge (good acceleration, timing, and forward penetration).
    * You like a crisper, more direct impact for counters and drives.

* **Choose Rakza 7 Soft if:**
    * You want easier opening loops, higher arc safety, and better short-game forgiveness.
    * You prefer a softer feel with more dwell for spin on compact strokes.
    * You value predictable control in receive, blocking, and allround rally stability.